<TEXT>
west germans are getting out 
their calculators and pondering whether they will be economic 
victors or victims as foreign troops begin leaving over the next 
few years 
west germany sees its mighty economic machine growing even 
stronger when land now occupied by foreign forces is made available 
for german development for the first time in four decades 
but many germans have become hooked on cashcarrying cold 
warriors and they are clearly concerned 
if all the americans leave its going to hurt each and every 
german americans spend enormous amounts of money here said 
harry spittler who owns a gift shop in kaiserslautern 
american officials say west germany gets an annual infusion of 
about 875 billion because of the us troop presence alone about 
200000 germans earn their livings directly from the american 
deployment 
if all goes well at conventional weapons talks in vienna the 
united states and soviet union will each lower their troop levels 
in central europe to 195000 apiece 
under that plan about 59000 us troops will leave west 
germany over the next five years there are currently 250000 
american soldiers here a figure that does not include dependents 
britain has said it also plans to reduce its troop levels in 
west germany by the mid1990s halving the current number of about 
66700 
the kaiserslautern area with about 70000 american troops and 
their dependents plus civilian workers has the greatest 
concentration of us troops outside the continental united states 
some of the largest us military installations in europe are in 
kaiserslautern including ramstein air base european headquarters 
for the us air force 
spittler 64 is a classic example of how some west germans hav 
developed an economic addiction to the foreign troops 
his clientele at harrys gift shop is almost exclusively 
american they are drawn by his huge stock of beer steins 
nutcracker dolls and cuckoo clocks german souvenirs that are 
especially coveted by gis scouting gifts to send to their families 
stateside 
the store clerks and spittler speak fluent english instead of 
hearing guten morgen customers are greeted with a cheery 
good morning 
if that doesnt make an american gi feel at home theres always 
the selection of american music coming from the shops stereo 
system on top of old smokey was playing one recent day 
no one expects the us military to pull completely out of west 
germany in the near future 
chancellor helmut kohl has said repeatedly west germany must 
continue to house american troops because there is always the 
chance a military threat to europe could arise again 
but even the most optimistic government officials concede that 
whatever troop cutbacks are in store weaning west germans from 
four decades of militarysupplied economic nourishment will not be 
easy 
american soldiers have their apartments here and they spend a 
lot of money shopping and in restaurants when disarmament comes 
naturally jobs will be lost as well as some economic power said 
juergen dietzen spokesman for the interior ministry of 
rhinelandpalatinate state 
rhinelandpalatinate is home to 64000 american troops more 
than 40000 state residents earn their livings either directly or 
indirectly from the american military presence dietzen said 
the state is already making plans for what to do after the 
closure of a major us air base at zweibruecken the base is to be 
shut in 1993 and there is concern for the more than 340 german 
nationals working there 
but the closing also demonstrates how west german officials seem 
to have optimistic views of life after the soldiers leave 
rhinelandpalatinate is charting plans to develop the base site 
into an industrial park with a commercial airport providing jobs 
for thousands of civilians 
we try not to get caught up in the problems that lie before 
us dietzen said we like to think of the new possibilities 
some west german communities are even trying to get the us 
government to include them as washington decides where to make its 
troop cuts 
frankfurt for example has been eyeing military sites nearby as 
possible places for economic expansion 
</TEXT>
