<TEXT>
three groups filed suit wednesday to block the 
armys plan to ship chemical weapons from west germany to johnston 
atoll saying the muntions pose a threat to the environment and 
people of the pacific 
meanwhile leaders of the 15nation south pacific forum meeting 
in port vila vanuatu issued a communique saying us plans to 
incinerate chemical weapons at johnston atoll could turn the 
pacific into the toxic waste disposal center of the world 
the communique called for closing the disposal plant once its 
current operations are completed 
greenpeace the institute for the advancement of hawaiian 
affairs and the world council of indigenous peopleshawaii contend 
the army hasnt adequately considered the risks involved in 
shipping the americanowned weapons across the ocean and 
incinerating them at the atoll 800 miles southwest of here 
we emphatically support the destruction of these weapons but 
not at the expense of the pacific environment said david 
chatfield chairman of greenpeace usa 
the groups represented by the sierra club legal defense fund 
said incineration of chemical weapons is an unproven procedure 
they said the government hasnt adequately considered other means 
of disposal including chemical neutralization 
they are seeking an injunction from the us district court here 
to block further movement of the munitions 
some 100000 rounds of nerve gas projectiles are to be shipped 
to johnston atoll during the next few months the army plans to 
store them at the facility and destroy them in an incinerator that 
is still being tested 
the suit names defense secretary dick cheney and michael p 
stone secretary of the army as defendants 
the armys action is also illegal because the army has done an 
extremely shoddy job of assessing the environmental impact of this 
scheme said skip spaulding a staff attorney for the sierra club 
legal defense fund indeed it appears that this shipment is 
merely a political gimmick to get west german chancellor helmut 
kohl reelected at the expense of us environmental laws 
the weapons from west germany would add 100000 rounds to the 
300000 rounds of nerve and mustard gas stored at johnston atoll 
since 1971 
they will be put in storage on johnston atoll until the army 
finishes testing an incinerator for the munitions the tests are to 
be completed late next year and fullscale destruction is not 
expected to begin until 1992 
the army has said moving the weapons and destroying them at 
johnston atoll would have minimal public health safety and 
environmental effects 
at the meeting of the south pacific forum prime minister bob 
hawke of australia argued in favor of the plan saying scientific 
evidence indicated the incineration was safe he said the project 
was in the interests of worldwide disarmament 
the pacific leaders whose governments represent about 25 
million people will discuss the issue friday with a us 
delegation 
</TEXT>
