christopher f edley who as president of the 
united negro college fund helped raise 556 million dollars over 18 
years announced wednesday that he will retire at the end of the 
year 
edley 62 who had a heart bypass operation seven years ago is 
retiring because of health problems the organization announced 
under edleys leadership the fund adopted its nowfamous 
advertising slogan a mind is a terrible thing to waste and 
became one of the best known charities in the nation 
the fund raised 10 million the year before edley became 
president last year it took in more than 50 million 
the fund also runs a capital campaign with a goal of raising 
250 million mainly for building projects money from the fund 
helps pay operating expenses at 41 institutions that enroll 48233 
students 
edley earned a law degree at harvard university after graduating 
from howard university in 1949 he was an assistant district 
attorney in philadelphia before becoming an officer at the ford 
foundation 
