<TEXT>
during his first week in office president 
alberto fujimori has quickly shaken up top government echelons and 
popular opinion seems to support his drive to stabilize the 
battered nation 
just hours after taking office on saturday fujimori strolled 
into the presidential palace for a ritual handshaking ceremony 
with the commanders of the army navy and air force 
when the names of the military chiefs were called peruvians 
were startled to learn that the heads of the navy and the air force 
werent the same officers who had been in power at lunchtime 
asked at his first news conference on sunday why he had removed 
adm alfonso panizo and air gen german vucetich fujimori replied 
the laws give this right to the president 
insiders said the president acted because the navy was rumored 
to have been fomenting a coup attempt and the air force general had 
been linked to corruption in the military 
fujimori later fired the nations four top police officials and 
his government called it a staff renovation but rumored 
corruption in law enforcement agencies was the likely reason 
the 52yearold president a mildlooking agronomist of japanese 
ancestry won an upset victory in june for a fiveyear term as 
president of perus 22 million citizens 
he promised fairness in government and honesty in leadership 
but no one expected him to act so decisively so quickly so far 
the publics reaction has been mostly positive 
fuji does not tremble the newspaper novedades proclaimed in 
a frontpage headline 
to prepare measures for combating ruinous inflation the 
president declared a twoday bank holiday he promised peruvians he 
would not touch individual savings accounts as happened earlier in 
the year in neighboring brazil fujimori said people shouldnt 
panic and they didnt 
caretas perus largest weekly news magazine called fujimori a 
house on fire and said he appeared to be shaking things up by 
going after everybody 
el comercio of lima perus biggest newspaper reported that a 
vast majority of people questioned after his inauguration gave 
fujimori a good rating 
the most important thing is the morality part said javier 
juaman a lima store clerk he was referring to fujimoris 
inaugural pledge to crack down on government corruption and make 
bureaucrats more sensitive to the problems of perus socalled 
ordinary people 
fujimori called perus legal system unfair to the masses of poor 
people and said the justice palace is better known on the street as 
the injustice palace 
one of fujimoris biggest challenges is the leftist shining path 
insurgency which has wreaked havoc in peru for years and defied 
military efforts to stifle it the president says the best way to 
defeat the rebels is by raising peruvians living standards and 
promoting economic development 
on tuesday fujimori took a walk for several blocks in downtown 
lima onlookers cheered and children shrieked foohee 
foohee which is how the first half of the presidents name is 
pronounced in spanish 
it was too early to tell how fujimoris street popularity would 
affect his ability to work with perus many political parties 
his grassroots coalition change 90 suffered serious defections 
before the inauguration and no one from the coalition wound up in 
fujimoris cabinet the coalition is in the minority in both houses 
of perus congress 
he appears to be truthful but hes also being very generic 
said sen miguel cruchaga belaunde of the democratic front 
coalition that groups presidential candidate famed novelist 
mario vargas llosa lost to fujimori in the most stunning upset in 
modern latin american politics 
fujimori had scored under 1 percent in opinion surveys at the 
beginning of the year but he swept to the front during the spring 
presidential campaign when voters became alienated by vargas 
llosas vow to introduce tough austerity measures to revitalize the 
economy 
the novelist was also tainted by the support he received from 
traditionally discredited political parties 
running on a platform emphasizing consensus fujimori took a 
centrist position in his campaign and managed to draw supporters 
from across party lines with his populist image 
legislators from many parties whooped and cheered during 
fujimoris inaugural address in the house of representatives 
minutes earlier the same lawmakers had booed and banged on 
their desks when the outgoing president alan garcia tried to make 
a farewell speech 
