the justice ministry has launched a new 
investigation into the 1984 police killing of a prosolidarity 
priest to determine if higherups of the former communist 
government were involved 
a new inquiry into the slaying of rev jerzy popieluszko 
officially was opened july 24 the justice ministry said tuesday in 
a statement to the official pap news agency 
the murder of the popular priest shocked the nation which last 
year elected a solidarityled government to replace the communists 
popieluszkos sermons counseling perseverance after the 
imposition of martial law in 1981 to crush solidarity had drawn 
tens of thousands of people and made him a national symbol of 
resistance to authoritarian communist rule 
four security service officers were convicted in a hastily held 
trial of abducting beating and drowning popieluszko in october 
1984 but communist prosecutors at the time said there was no 
evidence of higher involvement 
however the convicted ringleader of the killers capt grzegorz 
piotrowski hinted in a letter to former interior minister gen 
czeslaw kiszczak made public last month that the killing had been 
carried out with the knowledge of superiors 
the opening of the new inquiry comes only three weeks after the 
resignation of kiszczak who as head of the interior ministry was 
in charge of the security service at the time of the popieluszko 
killing 
the solidarityled government of prime minister tadeusz 
mazowiecki now has a civilian in charge of the interior ministry 
who is systematically scouring the department and replacing 
personnel 
