the 1990 farm bill approved by the house calls 
for about 53 billion to 55 billion in spending on crop support 
programs over the fiveyear life of the bill here at a glance 
are the major provisions and how they compare to the senate version 
of the bill 
 
the bill 
 
freezes target prices at 4 a bushel for wheat 275 a bushel 
for corn 261 for sorghum 236 for barley 73 cents a pound for 
cotton and 1071 per hundred pounds for rice same as senate 
oats would be set at 155 for 1991 with an increase each year of 
10 cents up to a maximum of 185 same as senate 
freezes milk prices at 1010 per hundred pounds same as 
senate 
continues the sugar price support at 18 cents a pound same as 
senate 
establishes a loan rate for soybeans of 525 a bushel but 
gives the agriculture secretary the option of making adjustments up 
or down 5 percent depending on surpluses though not to exceed 
540 in 1993 establishes a marketing loan for soybeans sunflower 
seed canola flax and safflower similar to senate though senate 
loan rate is 550 a bushel 
limits commodities deficiency payments to 100000 for a single 
farmer marketing loans to 100000 and total payments to 
200000 not in senate bill 
