<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures on iraq 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
land iraq the biblical mesopotamia or the land between two 
rivers took its name from uruq arabic for rocks 
presentday iraq covers 263090 square miles with mountains in the 
north and marshy flatlands in the south the tigris and euphrates 
rivers converge in the southeast to form the 120mile waterway 
known as shattalarab that flows into the persian gulf 
iraq is bounded by turkey to the north iran to the east the 
persian gulf to the southeast kuwait and saudi arabia to the south 
and jordan and syria to the west 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people a majority of iraqs 16 million people are shiite 
moslems but the country is ruled by sunni moslems there are small 
christian communities and an enclave in the north where most of the 
countrys rebellious 35 million kurds live the national language 
is arabic spoken by 81 percent of the population while another 15 
percent speak kurdish baghdad the capital has approximately 46 
million people 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
economy iraq has oil reserves of more than 100 billion 
barrels the 198088 war with iran sent oil exports plummeting but 
the iraqis built pipelines through neighboring turkey and saudi 
arabia and production is now back to at least 3 million barrels a 
day the war left iraq with a foreign debt of about 70 billion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history iraq part of the ottoman empire from the 16th 
century was captured by british forces in 1916 in 1921 it became 
a kingdom under a league of nations mandate administered by 
britain iraq became independent on july 14 1958 in a coup which 
established a militaryled council of sovereignty headed by gen 
qassim 
qassim was overthrown in 1963 and gen abdul salam aref became 
president succeeded by his brother abdul rahman aref in 1966 
in 1968 a successful coup brought by the bath party placed gen 
ahmed al bakr in power saddam hussein bakrs vice president since 
1969 became president in 1979 in a peaceful transfer of power 
in 1980 iraq invaded iran in a territorial dispute over the 
shattalarab waterway that evolved into a nearly eightyear war a 
un ceasefire halted the fighting on aug 20 1988 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900802-0030 </DOCNO>
