<TEXT>
most of the 13 million scofflaws who owe a 
total of 66 billion in federal taxes are ordinary workers and 
businesses but the biggest include a drug dealer some rich oil 
investors and a halfdozen giant bankrupt companies 
the internal revenue service says 21 taxpayers owe more than 50 
million apiece a total of 36 billion among them about 3300 are 
responsible for more than 145 billion of the agencys accounts 
receivable 
irs commissioner fred t goldberg jr told the senate 
governmental affairs committee on wednesday that the agency is 
making progress in reducing accounts receivable which are taxes 
that have been assessed but not paid 
he noted for example that the irs this year is collecting 
472000 in delinquencies for each staffer in the collections 
division up from 388000 two years ago 
at the same time however i want to emphasize that we have a 
long way to go and the task is exceedingly difficult goldberg 
said making a serious dent in accounts receivable he said will 
require modernization of the agencys 30yearold computer system 
more money for more personnel and training and further 
simplification of tax laws 
paul l posner associate director of congress general 
accounting office said the irs is losing the battle because 
accounts receivable over the past six years grew twice as fast as 
total tax receipts continuation of that trend could have a 
serious negative impact on voluntary taxpayer compliance he said 
this rapid outofcontrol growth in unpaid taxes threatens to 
overwhelm the irs and is absolutely unacceptable said sen john 
glenn dohio chairman of the governmental affairs committee 
accounts receivable grew from 30 billion in 1984 to 66 billion 
last year the figure represents a sixyear accumulation of income 
payroll and other taxes assessed but not paid it does not include 
27 billion that the irs believes will never be collected because 
of death bankruptcy and inability to locate the debtor 
because of errors and duplication the irs and gao agree the 66 
billion figure may be exaggerated by as much as 50 percent 
accounts receivable are not the same as the tax gap which 
is the difference in income taxes that are collected and what would 
be collected if individuals and businesses correctly reported their 
income and deductions the gap is expected to be about 100 billion 
this year alone 
goldberg said 025 percent of the accounts receivable cases 
represent more than 20 percent of delinquent dollars 
other highlights 
six cases totaling 14 billion involve bankruptcies five cases 
totaling 106 billion involve erroneous assessments irs made 
three of the errors and taxpayers made two and are being closed 
one 61 million case is awaiting a court decision one worth 73 
million involves an unidentified drug dealer 
two cases worth 191 million involve a dispute over the 
nowrepealed windfallprofits tax on oil production and 362 
million at stake in two cases likely will never be paid for a 
variety of reasons including fraudulent investments 
goldberg said president bushs irs budget for next year is a 
good start toward reducing accounts receivable because it would 
allow hiring 1050 new collection personnel he said a twoyear 
hiring freeze has left the agency is such a state that nearly 
800000 accounts totaling 18 billion cannot be worked because of 
lack of personnel 
john pepping an irs collections officer in the laguna niguel 
calif district said the personnel shortage there is so severe 
that as a rule no account under 50000 is sent to the field for 
collection he testified on behalf of the national treasury 
employees union which represents most irs workers 
</TEXT>
