<TEXT>
the united states has viewed the oilrich 
persian gulf region as a vital part of the world since the end of 
world war ii and has deployed a continuous naval presence in the 
region since the late 1940s 
the united states has based its policy in the region on the need 
to maintain the free flow of oil from saudi arabia with the 
worlds largest proven oil reserves and iraq which ranks second 
in proven reserves 
but us relations with the major powers in the area iraq 
iran and saudi arabia have often been rocky 
with the outbreak of the 1967 middle east war between israel and 
its arab neighbors iraq broke relations with the united states 
over its support for israel and usiraqi relations plunged into 
a deep freeze for more than 15 years 
iraq was placed on a list of countries that support terrorism as 
the united states accused the baghdad government of financing 
palestinian terrorist movements 
the region grew even more vital to this country when the 
oilproducing arab countries imposed an embargo against the united 
states and other western nations in 1973 sending oil prices 
soaring and exposing the vulnerability of us consumers to the 
volatile developments in the persian gulf 
as relations with iraq and the other oil producers deteriorated 
us links to the government of iran improved iran too was rich 
in oil and the united states could count on steady supplies from 
the late shah reza pahlavi in return for consistent sales of 
american weaponry to build up his military forces 
relations with iran came to an abrupt and tragic end when moslem 
shiite fundamentalists under the spiritual guidance of ayatollah 
ruhollah khomeini deposed the shah and took over the us embassy 
in tehran holding more than 50 americans hostage for 444 days 
beginning in 1979 
with its relations with baghdad and tehran mired in hostility 
the united states strove to develop good ties with the small 
monarchies bordering iran iraq and saudi arabia 
these oilrich countries in the shadow of their powerful 
neighbors turned to the united states for weapons sales and 
political support their dependence on the united states grew as 
iraq became increasingly menacing after it launched its september 
1980 war against iran 
official us policy was to remain neutral in the eightyear 
war but in an effort to obtain the release of american hostages 
held in lebanon by proiranian moslem extremists the united states 
in 1985 began secret arms sales to the khomeini government 
just before that the united states and iraq resumed diplomatic 
relations but the united states refused to sell iraq any weapons 
as the war dragged on and both combatants launched a barrage of 
attacks on oil tankers plying the gulf the united states spread 
its protection over kuwait agreeing to put us flags on kuwaiti 
oil tankers ships from the us seventh fleet escorted kuwaiti 
tankers through the gulf 
although still remaining neutral the us action was seen as 
benefiting iraq because it helped keep open the shipping channel 
that iraq needed to get its oil to foreign markets 
with the end of the iraniraq war the united states set about 
to substantially improve relations with the government of saddam 
hussein extending credit programs for us farm sales to iraq 
us oil companies sharply increased their purchases from iraq 
providing the iraqi government with badly needed cash american 
businesses pressed the bush administration to provide additional 
loan guarantees so they could enjoy an expected boom from iraqs 
postwar reconstruction 
however tensions between washington and baghdad escalated again 
earlier this year when us customs agents in cooperation with 
british authorities intercepted a shipment of devices said to be 
intended for iraqs nuclear program iraq vehemently denied the 
allegation but congress was skeptical citing iraqs continued 
development of chemical weapons 
in recent days both the house and senate have moved to adopt 
sanctions against iraq even as the administration was considering 
similar steps of its own 
</TEXT>
