<TEXT>
a federal board is calling for immediate 
inspection of all boeing 737s and several other airliners after 
investigators determined that a mechanical fault not a bomb 
likely destroyed a philippine jet 
philippine authorities had said they suspected a bomb in the may 
11 explosion and fire that killed eight people as the philippines 
air lines 737 was taxiing for takeoff on a domestic flight from 
manila 
but the national transportation safety board which has assisted 
in the philippine governments inquiry said wednesday that 
investigators found evidence of a possibly defective switch inside 
the jetliners center fuel tank and damaged wiring leading to the 
switch 
the investigation has found no evidence of a bomb an 
incendiary device or sabotage ntsb chairman james kolstad said 
in a letter to federal aviation administration chief james busey 
the safety board has no power to issue orders for emergency 
inspections of airliners but the faa does foreign airlines 
generally follow faa orders involving usbuilt planes 
the fourmember board urged busey to issue airworthiness 
directives calling for inspection of float switch wiring in all 
boeing 737s and in all planes among other airliner types where 
modifications have been made that might have caused damage to wires 
leading to switches in the fuel tanks 
boeing co documents show that nearly 1900 of its 737s are in 
use worldwide the number of other airliners that could be affected 
was not immediately clear 
the faa already has advised philippine air lines to inspect its 
remaining two 737s for possible wiring damage during installation 
of lights that shine on each planes tail to illuminate its logo 
kolstad said but he said there is evidence of other wire damage in 
the plane that may have occurred at the factory 
the safety board does not believe that this action is adequate 
because it does not address the problem of faulty float switches 
kolstad added 
although kolstad said investigators have not determined exactly 
what triggered the explosion he said 
it is possible that the combination of a faulty float switch 
and damaged wires providing a continuous power supply to the float 
switch may have caused an electrical arc or overheating of the 
switch leading to the ignition of the center fuel tank vapor 
the board chairman said laboratory examination of the switch 
from the philippine jet indicated defects that show it is 
possible that the switch did not pass inspection when originally 
assembled 
the manufacturer revere aerospace changed its method of 
building the switches three years ago but all 850 switches stocked 
by boeing were made before the change kolstad said in the letter 
the board questioned boeings procedures for inspecting the 
switches and said a testing technique should be developed that 
would ensure that the switches are free from defect that could 
cause an explosion or fire 
boeing spokesman tom cole said the airplane manufacturer has 
been participating in the investigation he said it probably 
already has sent out a service letter to other 737 users on 
implications of the philippine explosion 
cole said however he knew of no recommendations boeing had 
made for inspections or alterations 
we are cooperating fully in the investigation and we are 
advising our customers of whatever we learn he said 
safety board member jim burnett in a comment attached to 
kolstads letter said he preferred an even broader inspection 
affecting any airliner with a revere aerospace switch of the type 
used in the philippine jet 
burnett also called for an order that all such switches be 
tested and replaced if found defective 
