<TEXT>
kuwait is a small kingdom whose fabulous 
riches have sometimes made it the envy of the muchlarger neighbors 
that surround it 
baghdad has long claimed that the 6880squaremile kuwait is 
part of iraq although kuwait has been ruled by the alsabah family 
as an emirate since 1756 
kuwaits relatively freewheeling newspapers are read throughout 
the arab world and kuwait has long been a major donor of economic 
aid to poorer countries inside and outside the arab world 
recently prodemocracy activists mounted a campaign for 
restoration of the countrys parliament which had been suspended 
in 1986 after fierce attacks on the government by opposition 
deputies 
the emir sheik jaber alahmed alsabah later introduced an 
interim national council with 50 elected members and 25 appointed 
charged with paving the way for restoration of a full parliament 
kuwaits oil tanker fleet was a frequent target of iranian 
attacks during the eightyear iraniraq war and iranian missiles 
were sent into kuwait at the height of the hostilities 
shiite moslem terrorists backed by iran launched repeated 
attacks in kuwait during the war including the successful bombings 
of the french and american embassies and an abortive attempt to 
kill the emir 
the kuwaitis are an ancient seafaring people but more than half 
the population of 18 million are foreigners mainly arab 
including 300000 palestinians 
most kuwaitis are sunni moslem but 30 percent adhere to the 
rival shiite sect shiites of iranian descent number nearly 
150000 the alsabah clan has ruled kuwait as an emirate since 
they settled there in the 18th century after trekking from the 
arabian hinterland 
kuwait lives on its oil revenue reached 30 billion in 1983 but 
has been declining since because of a drop in oil prices and 
production curbs 
kuwait currently produces about 15 million barrels of oil a day 
and has reserves of 897 billion barrels 128 percent of world 
reserves and enough to last for more than 250 years 
little grows in the desert climate so the emirate has to import 
nearly all its food 
the mongols arab caliphs and ottomans were by turn overlords of 
the bleak and largely unpopulated land until 1899 when the british 
became the dominant power in the region kuwait gained its 
independence in 1961 
</TEXT>
