<TEXT>
a judge who ruled los angeles countys board 
of supervisors had illegally drawn its districts to keep hispanics 
from getting elected rejected as nonsensical a plan offered by the 
board to solve the problem 
us district judge david kenyon on wednesday called for a new 
plan raising the prospect of a radical shift in the countys 
balance of power 
kenyon said the remedy offered by the board was a nonsensical 
distortion of existing supervisorial districts a calloused 
interpretation of the voting rights act and is insensitive to the 
needs of hispanic and black residents 
the judge set a hearing for today to consider alternative plans 
from civil rights groups and the us justice department 
civil rights groups and the department had sued in 1988 
accusing the supervisors of deliberately spreading the hispanic 
population across several districts when they changed voting 
boundaries after the 1980 census 
though hispanics make up about 35 percent of the countys 87 
million residents the fivemember board has not had an elected 
hispanic member in 115 years 
on june 7 kenyon ruled against the supervisors concluding they 
violated the voting rights act 
the boards conservatives responded by drafting a plan that 
created a hispanic majority in one liberal board members district 
while also preserving the boards conservative majority it was 
this plan kenyon rejected wednesday 
the next redistricting plans to be submitted by the american 
civil liberties union the government and a mexicanamerican group 
could greatly increase hispanic political clout and overturn the 
conservative majority 
that could have profound implications for funding in such areas 
as health and social services 
conservative supervisor mike antonovich denounced the judges 
decision and said he will appeal 
