<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of kuwait is the latest 
thrust for ambitious president saddam hussein 
saddam earlier this year threatened to destroy half of israel 
with internationally outlawed chemical weapons if israel tried to 
attack any iraqi military facilities 
western nations are nervous about iraqs military posturing 
police have arrested several people in britain on charges they 
were trying to smuggle nuclearbomb triggers to baghdad 
police in britain and other european countries also intercepted 
shipments that they said were parts of a gigantic gun capable of 
firing chemical or nuclear shells into israel 250 miles west of 
the iraqi border 
seeking to don the arab nationalist mantle of the late egyptian 
president gamal abdel nasser saddam has acquired a reputation for 
ruthlessness 
obsessed about security he ordered the march 15 execution of 
iranianborn londonbased journalist farzad bazoft who had tried 
to gather information about a huge explosion at a 
militaryindustrial complex 
iraq has the secondlargest known oil reserves in the world 
after saudi arabia more than 100 billion barrels 
using oil revenue and his absolute power saddam initiated 
ambitious social educational and economic development programs in 
the 1970s 
his eightyear war with iran left him with the arab worlds most 
formidable and battletrained army but his nation was also saddled 
with about 70 billion in war debts of which 10 billion to 20 
billion was owed to kuwait saddam had demanded that kuwait write 
off that debt 
saddam launched an economic reconstruction drive after the 
august 1988 ceasefire with iran but was constantly strapped for 
cash 
he turned his attention to kuwait whose roaring oil production 
was helping glut the market and drive prices down cutting saddams 
precious revenues 
iraq claimed kuwait was stealing oil from a border oil field and 
demanded kuwaits bubiyan island which is opposite iraqs only 
outlets to the sea 
baghdad has even claimed for years that kuwait is part of iraq 
a majority of iraqs 16 million people are shiite moslems the 
same branch of islam as most iranians who the iraqis were at war 
with between 1980 and 1988 but iraq is ruled by sunni moslems 
there are small christian communities and an enclave in the 
north where most of the countrys rebellious 35 million kurds live 
captured by britain in 1916 iraq became independent in 1932 a 
military coup in 1958 ended the monarchy saddam came to power in 
1979 and gradually tightened the grip of his ruling baath socialist 
party 
