<TEXT>
orders to factories for manufactured goods 
slumped in june for the third time this year the government said 
thursday the report added to analysts fears of a possible 
recession that were intensified by rising oil prices resulting from 
iraqs invasion of kuwait 
the economy is walking on a precipice and doesnt need 
something to come up and give it a shove said robert g 
dederick chief economist with the northern trust co of chicago 
shortly after the iraqi army pushed into neighboring kuwait oil 
prices soared amid fears the invasion would reduce the worlds oil 
supply at the same time the commerce department reported a 15 
percent drop in orders for both durable and nondurable factory 
goods more evidence of economic weakness 
were in a precarious position on the edge of a recession 
said thomas runiewicz an economist with the wefa group in bala 
cynwyd pa with the problems in the middle east and the threat 
of higher oil prices that may be just enough to push us over 
on the other hand chairman michael boskin of president bushs 
council of economic advisers contended that a 25 percent hike in 
oil prices could be absorbed by the economy without halting its 
growth 
even if the higher price is enforced our economy today is 
much better able to absorb modest price increases boskin told 
the congressional joint economic committee 
iraq and kuwait produce onefifth of the total oil produced by 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries and their oil 
accounts for an estimated 5 percent of daily us consumption 
in its report on factory orders the commerce department said 
the decline was concentrated in durable goods bigticket items 
expected to last more than three years they fell 28 percent to 
1251 billion after a 22 percent advance a month earlier 
nondurable orders were flat at 1123 billion 
dederick noted that factory orders have bounced up and down 
throughout the first half of the year and as a result the 
manufacturing sector is really just spinning its wheels 
orders plummeted 55 percent in january the sharpest drop 
since a 70 percent decrease in december 1974 they then rose 18 
percent in february and 40 percent in march before dropping 21 in 
april orders were up 22 percent in may 
and as orders decline industry tends to cut production and 
jobs in fact the labor department reported earlier the loss of 
31000 factory jobs in june 
because many factory items particularly durable goods are 
purchased through loans the manufacturing sector has borne the 
brunt of high interest rates engineered by the federal reserve as 
its sought to slow the economy to dampen inflationary pressures 
but even if the higher oil prices do not jolt the economy into 
recession they will tend to drive up overall living costs and 
hamper the central banks antiinflation efforts 
the factory orders report did contain at least one hopeful sign 
a 06 percent gain to 361 billion in the key category of 
nondefense capital goods this barometer of business investment 
plans had fallen 18 percent in may 
over half of the durables decline was in defense goods which 
dropped 203 percent to 80 billion excluding defense orders 
would have dropped 07 percent 
