<TEXT>
killer bees humbug its the ornery red 
imported fire ant that is threatening life and limb in the south 
these days 
and the situation keeps getting worse says the agriculture 
department in 1957 fire ants occupied about 27 million acres by 
1985 their domain was 230 million acres stretching from texas to 
virginia and puerto rico 
regina wiggen of the departments agricultural research service 
said people throughout the south have grudgingly surrendered 
ground to fire ants since the pests were first seen in the united 
states near mobile ala in 1918 
wiggen associate editor of the agencys agricultural research 
magazine wrote that fire ants are a threat to humans and 
livestock they also destroy or disfigure the landscape with their 
mounds 
in the ants wake playground and picnic areas lie abandoned 
parks disfigured golf courses churned up and cemeteries damaged 
she said no one who is hypersensitive to stinging insects should 
risk being stung 
all of this is old stuff to millions of southerners who have 
learned to look carefully where they sit or lie in the great 
outdoors but the ants may be getting antsy about moving on 
for years wiggen said scientists believed the ants have a 
limited tolerance of cold weather in their native argentina they 
dont range south of 38 degrees latitude which is comparable to 
the pests northernmost range in the united states 
but lately there has been concern that the imported red fire ant 
has been mingling with black varieties which might produce a 
coldtolerant fire ant 
isolated colonies have been spotted in arizona and california 
the december 1989 issue of nursery digest warned that once 
established in california fire ants probably will spread to much 
of the western seaboard 
the usda for many years worked with states to fight fire ants 
with chemicals and poisoned bait wiggen said that between 1957 and 
1977 millions of acres were treated with the insecticide mirex 
but without enduring avail 
now she said we know that widespread application of toxic 
chemicals may put the environment at more risk than the ants 
the magazines cover story by jessica morrison silva tells about 
the life cycle of fire ants how they threaten homeowners public 
lands and farming areas the colony is based on a queen which has 
a rather bizarre sex life 
after a virgin queen mates in midair she descends to the 
ground silva said no longer needing wings she now chews or 
breaks them off the remaining wing muscles are used as a 
nutritional source for her in establishing the new colony and in 
egg production 
parasites and other natural weapons are being examined as 
possible methods of curbing the pests scientists are seeking a 
complex of fire ant disease and natural pests that will do the job 
meanwhile africanized bees the socalled killer bees of 
hollywood fame are still moving north and may cross the 
usmexico border any time now say usda officials 
while these aggressive bee can be threatening they still only 
sting from one end the fire ant according to usda entomologists 
grabs you with its jaws and socks it to you with its tail stinger 
both the bite and sting are painful 
</TEXT>
