<TEXT>
for 234 years the alsabah family ruled kuwait 
but on thursday the onceproud dynasty was shattered by a lighting 
invasion by iraq 
at least one member of the royal family was reported to have 
been killed and the emir himself sheik jaber alahmed alsabah 
and his crown prince sheik saad abdullah alsabah fled to 
neighboring saudi arabia 
this is a black thursday in the annals of not only the 
alsabah dynasty but also arab solidarity one kuwaiti government 
official said speaking on condition of anonymity 
egypts middle east news agency quoted witnesses as saying sheik 
fahd alahmed alsabah the emirs brother was gunned down as he 
tried to defend the emirs palace persian gulf diplomats speaking 
on condition of anonymity later confirmed he was dead 
members of the alsabah family like other royal families in the 
rest of the gulf region fill many key posts in the government 
army police and private sector they number more than 1000 
oil has given kuwait one of the highest per capita incomes in 
the world about 20000 but this has not meant peace for the 
tiny persian gulf country of 18 million people 
the 64yearold emir sheik jaber has come in for much of the 
turbulence 
when his country gained independence from britain in 1961 he 
was named minister of finance and economy just as iraq was 
claiming sovereignty britain had to bring in troops to get the 
iraqis to back off 
by the time he moved up the ranks to prime minister crown 
prince and finally emir late 1977 kuwait was a country in the 
throes of a parliamentary crisis 
by 1980 parliament was restored and kuwait was an arab pioneer 
of westernstyle democracy 
but soon the iraqiran war broke out kuwait was a leading 
supporter of iraq bearing 15 billion of baghdads war costs 
from 1980 to 1988 kuwait was caught in between the fighting of 
two neighboring powers iraq and iran hearing the sound of gunfire 
from the front only 90 miles away 
iran dedicated to spreading its islamic revolution and angry at 
kuwait for supporting iraq attacked kuwaiti shipping lanes and oil 
facilities the united states later protected reflagged kuwaiti 
tankers in the gulf 
kuwaitis also believe iran was behind a spate of terrorism that 
began with the 1983 car bombings of us and french embassies 
seventeen proiranian shiite moslem terrorists were convicted 
for those attacks and demands for their release were hammered home 
with more attacks 
bombs were planted in downtown locations at oil installations 
and at seafront cafes in may 1985 there was a carbomb attack on 
sheik jabers life but he escaped with minor injuries 
with the end of the war the emir hoped baghdad would settle its 
longstanding border dispuate with kuwait but it never did 
