<TEXT>
rebels turned their backs on president 
samuel does troops on thursday and prepared to fight each other a 
source close to guerrilla leader prince johnson said 
diplomats said the rivalry between johnson and his foe charles 
taylor could prolong this west african nations 7monthold civil 
war for weeks 
johnsons fighters withdrew thursday from key positions they 
have occupied in central monrovia 
that leaves the capital open to renewed occupation by does 
soldiers who massacred up to 600 men women and children sunday in 
an attack on st peters lutheran church those killed were among 
thousands of civilians who have sought sanctuary at churches and 
embassies from tribal reprisals by troops and rebels 
hundreds of civilians again started fleeing from the city 
wednesday 
only a few fighters of johnsons independent patriotic front 
were visible in areas of downtown monrovia which they captured 
from does troops earlier in the week 
gunfire broke out in parts of the city that were firmly under 
johnsons control on wednesday 
a big fire occurred in eastern monrovia but it was unclear 
whether the blaze was touched off by the fighting the fire raged 
out of control because there is no longer a fire brigade in the 
capital 
monrovias 500000 residents have been without running water 
electricity and food supplies for nearly a month 
an american who has lived in liberia for years and claims to be 
close to johnson said the rebel leader was turning his forces 
around to confront taylors troops who were advancing from behind 
him 
like the other sources the american spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
johnson broke with taylor and his national patriotic front in 
february and accuses his rival of being a libyan stooge and a 
communist johnson has said he does not share taylors aspirations 
to lead liberia 
taylor appears to have the larger of the two rebel forces but 
johnson struck into the capital earlier in the bid to unseat doe 
who is holed up in his heavily fortified executive mansion 
no faction has established clear superiority and its not at 
all clear that there will be an early end to the conflict one 
diplomat said 
in the fighting since rebels invaded from neighboring ivory 
coast last december about 5000 people have been killed most of 
them civilians 
the insurgents accuse doe of corruption and human rights abuses 
he has ruled this west african nation of more than 2 million people 
since taking power in a 1980 coup 
johnson told reporters on wednesday that he would be prepared to 
discuss with taylor a joint attack on doe if both rebel forces were 
in a position to advance on the presidential mansion but taylors 
troops remained blocked by government troops six miles from the 
city center 
johnson also said he would welcome a un peacekeeping force in 
liberia 
we are not going to fight a neutral force he said we 
would lay down our arms and let the neutral people carry on their 
peacekeeping operation 
he held his news conference at his headquarters on suburban 
bushrod island the reporters car came under fire on its way back 
from there first from the rebels then from government troops 
