us rep floyd flake was indicted thursday on 
conspiracy and fraud charges alleging he embezzled thousands of 
dollars from his church and a related senior citizens housing 
project 
the indictment lists 17 counts against flake a 45yearold 
ordained minister and nine against his wife margarett 42 for 
activities between 1983 and 1989 
it alleged that flake a democrat who represents new yorks 6th 
congressional district illegally diverted a total of 141700 from 
church and housing funds to his own use and failed to report it as 
taxable income 
flake denied the charges and a lawyer for mrs flake said they 
added credence to the idea that evenhanded treatment is not 
being accorded to minority politicians 
flake is pastor of the 156yearold allen african methodist 
church in queens which built the 300unit allen senior citizens 
apartments in 1981 with a 10 million federal loan 
the church operates the complex with a 100000 monthly subsidy 
from the department of housing and urban development the 
indictment charged that between 1983 and 1987 the flakes embezzled 
75000 from the complex 
us attorney andrew maloney said the money was siphoned off in 
6000 increments from quarterly hud allocations of 9000 set 
aside for transporting senior citizen residents of the center on 
local business he said the actual transportation costs were only 
3000 a quarter 
the indictment alleged that flake took an additional 66700 
from a special church ministerial expense fund account for his 
own use between 1983 and 1988 again not reporting the money as 
taxable income 
maloney said the churchs 6000 parishoners apparently were 
unaware of the alleged theft because the special account was 
managed by the flakes themselves 
flakes attorney gustave newman said the money was used for 
church purposes and the charges would not stand up in court 
newman also said the case would not affect flakes plans to seek 
reelection to a third term in the house this year 
ted wells mrs flakes lawyer described his client as really 
only a secretary who signed tax forms and checks but had no 
substantive involvement in the operations 
the charges included one count of conspiracy two of fraud and 
six of tax evasion against each of the two defendants in addition 
flake is charged with four counts of filing false tax returns and 
four of making false financial statements 
if convicted on all 17 counts flake could be sentenced to a 
maximum of 87 years in prison and fined up to 395 million his 
wife could face penalties of 55 years in prison and fines of up to 
21 million 
wells accused maloney of furthering what he said was a pattern 
of unfair prosecutions against minority politicians 
this indictment is unfair treatment of a minority female and 
by treating her this way you just add fuel to the fire that 
prosecutors are not handling these cases in an evenhanded 
fashion he said 
