wheat farmers will have to idle more of their 
base acreage next year to qualify for federal price supports and 
subsidies on their crop agriculture secretary clayton yeutter 
announced thursday 
tentatively he said the 1991 acreage reduction program for 
wheat or arp probably will be in the range of 10 percent to 20 
percent farmers were required to set aside only 5 percent of their 
acreage base this year 
yeutter said he could not make a final determination until 
congress completes work on the 1990 farm bill and it is accepted by 
the administration both the house and senate have passed versions 
of the bill 
sen bob dole rkan and others had pressured yeutter to make 
a preliminary announcement of the 1991 wheat program in time for 
winter wheat planting this fall 
in a letter to dole yeutter emphasized the announcement was 
tentative and that it could change because of final provisions 
approved in the 1990 farm bill 
yeutter also pledged that the agriculture department would 
continue to use export subsidies under the export enhancement 
program or eep to keep wheat competitive in world markets 
under eep exporters are given surplus governmentowned 
commodities as subsidies or bonuses so they can reduce prices 
paid by selected foreign buyers wheat has been the biggest 
beneficiary of the eep subsidies 
the program was started in 1985 to help meet export competition 
by foreign shippers notably the european economic community 
yeutter said eep currently is available to 41 countries he said 
these initiatives can be utilized at any time to compete 
headtohead with the europeans 
