<TEXT>
the iraqi conquest of kuwait has catapulted 
iraq to the top ranks of world oil powers and poses new economic 
risks for the united states and other countries dependent on 
imported oil private analysts said thursday 
it was unclear whether the iraqi invasion of its tiny neighbor 
at the northern tip of the persian gulf would slow or halt kuwaits 
oil production but the conflict seemed to signal an important 
shift in the balance of world oil power 
the energy department said it did not see an imminent threat to 
the united states or an immediate price runup and said it had no 
planws to tap the nations emergency oil stockpile 
iraq being the dominant military power in the area could end 
up controlling a quarter of world oil supplies said 
christopher flavin a vice president of the worldwatch institute 
just overnight it doubled its share 
by grabbing control of kuwait iraqi president saddam hussein 
added about 94 billion barrels of oil reserves to his countrys own 
100 billion barrels that makes iraq second only to saudi arabia in 
world ranking for oil reserves according to the american petroleum 
institute an industry trade group 
the saudis traditional close allies of kuwait have 255 billion 
barrels of oil reserves 
the united states holds about 26 billion barrels of reserves 
but us oil production has declined rapidly over the past four 
years while consumption has increased as a result 50 percent of 
oil used in the united states is imported and many experts say 
this reliance makes america vulnerable to manipulation of the oil 
market 
the top 10 us oil suppliers are saudi arabia which provides 
15 percent of imports venezuela 13 percent nigeria 125 
percent canada 12 percent iraq 76 percent mexico 6 percent 
virgin islands 36 percent and britain angola and algeria a 
combined 97 percent kuwait supplies about 2 percent 
like kuwait the united arab emirates at the southern end of the 
gulf are vulnerable to iraqi military might the emirates control 
about 100 billion barrels of oil reserves and were the recent 
target of iraqi verbal assaults against excessive oil production by 
members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
president bush signed an order thursday banning us imports of 
iraqi products including oil freezing control of iraqi financial 
assets in the united states and forbidding exports to iraq a 
complete trade embargo 
iraqs oil should be easily replaceable from other sources since 
one barrel of oil is pretty much equivalent to any other barrel 
especially in a time of glutted oil markets like the present 
analysts say iraq by the same token should be able to find other 
sources of wheat and rice it may no longer buy from the united 
states under bushs order unless other nations also ban exports to 
iraq 
oil prices on the world market jumped sharply in reaction to the 
iraqi invasion but flavin and other analysts said the more 
unsettling implication of saddams action is his expanded clout in 
the gulf and his influence over future supplies 
the saudis the worlds largest oil exporters and the no 1 
supplier to the united states are sitting there quaking in their 
boots out of fear that saddam might invade their kingdom or seek 
a voice in running their oil affairs said dillard spriggs 
president of new yorkbased petroleum analysis ltd 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas said the iraqi army might not stop 
at kuwaits borders 
if iraq succeeds i believe that saudi arabia might be next 
and then saddam hussein would have a stranglehold on the wests oil 
supply bentsen said 
bushs chief economic adviser michael boskin told the 
congressional joint economic committee that the us economy was 
not threatened by the impact of iraqs takeover of kuwait even if 
it led to a 25 percent jump in oil prices 
boskin conceded that such a large rise in prices would cause 
some economic damage in the united states but said it would be more 
harmful to japan because of its greater dependence on oil imports 
japan gets virtually all its oil from foreign sources 
also on capitol hill the senate extended by one month bushs 
authority to tap into the 580million barrel strategic petroleum 
reserve an emergency oil storage system in the event of a supply 
squeeze the senate action was not directly linked to the iraqi 
invasion but senators said the gulf crisis served to underscore 
the fragile nature of middle east oil production and transportation 
all of the opec countries at least all of those in the 
middle east will be intimidated by iraq said sen j bennett 
johnston dla chairman of the senate energy and natural 
resources committee iraq will be able to set such prices as it 
wants 
henson moore the deputy secretary of energy told reporters at 
energy department headquarters that the administration was not 
considering tapping into the emergency reserve which he said 
contains the equivalent of 75 days worth of oil consumption 
we do not see any imminent threat to the united states 
by the loss of iraqi oil moore said nor do we see any longterm 
significant increase in prices 
