were in kuwait at the request of a revolutionary council 
most people here seemed unaware what revolutionary council had 
called for their governments ouster 
instead scenes from the occupied city thursday bordered on the 
bizarre 
in one area of the city about 30 kuwaitis stood patiently in 
line waiting to rent videocassette movies for the night the 
reason in the words of one woman is that most residents are 
staying at home sitting tight 
many kuwait autos have been left in the streets some not even 
parked but merely abandoned as if the drivers saw the approaching 
troops and fled roads and sidewalks in parts of the city have been 
damaged and churned up by the hundreds of tanks that entered kuwait 
some of the iraqi troops have been seen driving around the 
capital in newly confiscated kuwaiti police cars 
at a circular intersection iraqi troops mill about sitting 
eating and talking ground rocketlaunchers stand idle nearby 
ready to be fired if necessary about 100 soldiers meander about 
outside the newly occupied sheraton hotel in groups of 10 
in downtown kuwait the streets are largely deserted with none 
of the usual bustle of taxis and buses only in the suburbs do 
local residents dare to go outside for long though some are still 
fearful of further incidents with the invading forces life in the 
suburbs however seems basically normal 
the only sign of domestic unrest was spot panicbuying in the 
supermarkets where residents shopped quickly and headed right home 
