<TEXT>
washington ap the house began debate on a major civil rights 
bill thursday and voted to put a ceiling on punitive damages that 
courts can award to women who are victims of intentional job 
discrimination 
this will lay the unfounded fears to rest said the chairman 
of the judiciary committee rep jack brooks dtexas said as the 
house approved the cap 289134 
punitive damages for women religious minorities and the 
disabled could be no more than 150000 or the amount of 
compensatory damages awarded by the court whichever is larger 
the house worked into the night thursday on the but put off a 
vote on passage and other major floor action until friday 
the bill is the top item on the civil rights communitys 
congressional shopping list and would effectively reverse five 
supreme court decisions last year it is advancing under threat of 
a presidential veto with the bush administration saying it would 
lead to hiring quotas for members of minority groups 
provisions range from a ban on racial harrassment in the 
workplace to barriers against reopening courtapproved fairhiring 
plans 
the most controversial provisions would make it easier for those 
claiming to be victims of job discrimination to win lawsuits 
against employers based on statistics 
the ceiling on damages was designed to ease business concerns 
about the potential for huge openended jury awards for women 
victimized by discrimination it also was aimed at winning support 
among southern democrats 
liberal sponsors of the bill split over the issue rep don 
edwards dcalif chairman of the civil rights subcommittee of the 
judiciary committee voted against it education and labor 
committee chairman rep augustus hawkins dcalif voted for it 
the southern democrats voted with us on this cap and most of 
them will now support us when the house turns to a major 
amendment that would limit not only punitive but all damages to 
100000 said hawkins 
that proposal has been championed by rep john lafalce dny 
and has been praised by the bush administration as a step away from 
quotas sponsors say it would wreck the bill 
hawkins said sponsors would beat back the lafalce amendment by 
a whopping good vote 
womens groups have been opposing such ceilings saying they 
would be unfair in view of unlimited punitive damages allowed in 
the case of deliberate racial discrimination in the workplace 
the house earlier had approved 39724 an amendment making 
clear that no hiring quotas would be required under the bill 
similar language was included in the measure when it was approved 
by the judiciary committee but lawmakers wanted a chance to vote 
on it separately 
republican critics scoffed that the noquotas amendment amounted 
to nothing more than a cosmetic exercize i cant believe the 
charade of it all declared rep nancy johnson rconn 
civil rights forces scoff at the charge that the bill would lead 
to quotas 
if anyone raises the subject of quotas i want to know where 
it is said rep john conyers dmich there is no reference to 
quotas in this bill 
womens groups have been crusading against the lafalce measure 
noting that there is no cap on damages that courts can now award to 
victims of racial discrimination in the workplace 
the decision by lafalce to sponsor the rival plan plainly irked 
fellow democrats who positioned the proposed amendment for floor 
action in such a way that it could be offered only by republican 
leader bob michel of illinois or someone designated by him 
as debate began rep f james sensenbrenner jr rwis 
blasted the bill sponsors for fashioning a measure that exempts 
congress itself 
the same thing ought to apply in the congress of the united 
states sensenbrenner said he urged lawmakers to end the 
hypocrisy of us insulating ourselves from our own laws once and 
for all this afternoon 
black lawmakers launched the debate by pleading for approval of 
the bill 
this is the single most important civil rights legislation 
since the 1964 civil rights act said rep al wheat dmo he 
said it carried a simple message that discrimination and 
particularly intentional discrimination based on race is not 
acceptable in america 
rep ron dellums dcalif attacked the lafalce substitute 
declaring there is no substitute for justice 
