<TEXT>
theres a moment in alan lomaxs wonderful 
american patchwork series on pbs when you understand the 
incredible power of cultural forces and the ingenuity of his 
anthropologists vision 
lomax takes us to a joyous new orleans neighborhood parade at 
carnival time when black men don gorgeously ornate mardi gras 
indian costumes and take to the streets for ritual dance duels 
with rival tribes 
he shows us their regalia and littleknown rituals and then 
almost casually his video camera tilts down to show their feet 
which slide along to the music in a distinctive groundhugging 
step 
they he cuts to a shot of bare feet dancing the identical step 
the camera pulled back to reveal the dancers of a west african 
village street parade 
it is a thoughtful clever touch immutable as chromosomes that 
gliding groundhugging dance step has come here from africa and 
has survived intact for hundreds of years in the proud cultural 
heritage of black americans 
african culture arrived here along the nonverbal route he 
explains deprived of language it kept its body language its 
enormously rich oral and nonverbal traditions 
the final episode of his fine fivepart series airs tonight on 
pbs like the others its filled with music color stories and 
songs from the patchwork quilt of american culture that somehow is 
more than the sum of its parts 
the human species for 90000 years has devoted itself to 
communications systems to music dance songs said lomax who 
with his father john a lomax compiled the library of congress 
distinguished archive of american folk song 
now that its beginning to slip away from us it begins to 
look mighty precious he said 
the series second episode explored the musical traditions of 
southwest louisianas vital cajun culture from the rowdy 
horseback gathering of the communitys mardi gras gumbo to its 
pastoralist origins in western france 
the third episode the land where blues began was a moving 
look at the music of the mississippi delta what lomax calls the 
powerful bitter poetry of an oppressed people 
lomax interviews the mule skinners who hauled the earth to build 
the mississippi river levees to hear the work songs and 
hollers they sing is to see the human face of a fundamentally 
american music its powerful stuff 
appalachian journey followed the britons who settled the 
eastern mountains where the isolation gave their heritage time 
to reorganize itself and led to the creation of bluegrass music 
our first genuine folk orchestra 
the final episode dreams and songs of the noble old 
features elderly balladeers and musicians who pass their music to 
the young 
its not preservation its process lomax said its 
keeping things going 
lomax a research associate in anthropology for columbia 
university and hunter college believes that our centralized 
electronic communications system is imposing standardized 
massproduced and cheapened cultures everywhere 
human beings and human affairs he says are 90 percent 
cultural our cultures give us ways of thinking feeling 
communicating and adapting to our environment that are unique to 
human beings 
if those absolutely important things are ignored of how we 
speciated how we adapted to the planet then were going to lose 
something precious he said there wont be anywhere to go and 
no place to come home to 
american patchwork is a joint production of the university 
of north carolina center for public television the national 
endowment for the artss media program the corporation for public 
broadcasting and pbs 
although the series wraps up friday night check your local 
listings carefully north carolina public tv spokeswoman chancy 
kapp said the success of the show was such that local rebroadcasts 
and even a pbs repeat may be in the cards 
</TEXT>
