<TEXT>
in one day the defense minister was 
replaced and 143 officers retired it was peaceful unlike many 
military changes in latin america but some venezuelans wonder how 
long that will contine 
similar promotions and retirements have occurred often in 
venezuelas 32 years as one of the stablest democracies of latin 
america with no problems or thought of a coup 
fears of the military taking a hand arise now because of an 
economic crisis that never seems to ease a sharp increase in crime 
and reports of corruption scandals involving billions of dollars 
a dozen prominent members of the governing democratic action 
party were cleared of corruption charges by the partys executive 
committee which caused a storm of protest from opposition and 
independent politicians 
on july 11 a public court issued arrest warrants on corruption 
charges for 12 other democratic action leaders including former 
interior minister jose angel ciliberto all went into hiding before 
police arrived and most are believed to have left the country 
jose vicente rangel a political analyst and former congressman 
said on a television program that a coup was possible even after 
such a long period of democracy 
he quoted surveys conducted by organizations of the utmost 
reliability as indicating 20 percent of venezuelans openly 
favored a military takeover and another 20 percent were indifferent 
venezuelans always supported democracy but now democracy is 
being associated with evils committed by political parties and 
politicians he told an associated press reporter the surveys 
mean four out of 10 venezuelans are potential supporters of a coup 
detat 
luis herrera campins a social christian who was president in 
197883 said democracy in venezuela is not 100 percent 
guaranteed especially if dissatisfaction and social protest 
keep growing 
others see coup rumors as a warning but not a real possibility 
it could be a way to wish evil on the thing blamed for so many 
frustrations the government said teodoro petkoff of the 
socialist movement party 
venezuelan leaders learned early last year that dissatisfaction 
can turn to violence at least 300 people were killed in riots 
after president carlos andres perez administered an economic shock 
treatment that included raising bus fares 30 percent and ending 
food subsidies 
perez slowed the program because of the riots and after 18 
months 72 percent of venezuelans still spend 70 percent of their 
incomes on food 
unemployment is slightly more than 10 percent by official 
figures but at least 14 percent according to labor unions when 
the underemployed are added the rate is well above 50 percent 
the bloated bureacracy has not been affected however it 
provides jobs for 12 million venezuelans or 20 percent of the 
nations labor force 
at least 30 percent of our population suffers from 
malnutrition said jose curiel a member of congress from the 
opposition social christians our hospitals simply dont work 
water is scarce public services are collapsing in its attempt 
at economic reform the government said most of the 400odd public 
companies would be sold quickly to private investors those 
companies are blamed for most of the nations 35 billion foreign 
debt and chronic deficits estimated at up to 2 billion annually 
no significant company has yet been sold partly due to fears of 
massive layoffs and labor unrest 
stateowned companies provide jobs for members of political 
parties mainly democratic action and the social christians and 
are a major base of union power the venezuelan labor confederation 
recently warned the government against layoffs at the main steel 
plant which has 18000 employees 
technical studies say at least 3000 should be dismissed if the 
plant is to stop losing money unions describe the studies as 
socially and politically destabilizing 
many venezuelans see increasing crime as an outgrowth of 
unemployment 
in two recent cases thieves killed the son of a former 
government minister and gunmen took over the home of the argentine 
ambassador 
tony bianchi editor of the daily journal in caracas said 25 of 
the newspapers 80 staff members had been attacked in recent months 
they included jules waldman the founder and chairman who died 
of injuries inflicted by thieves who invaded his home in june 
waldman 77 was a new yorker who spent more than 40 years in 
venezuela 
robberies and killings have become so frequent rangel said 
that venezuelan society is defenseless nobody is safe not even 
at home and streets are a trap for all 
</TEXT>
