<TEXT>
in the world of advertising dentsu is king in 
japan its also a kingmaker 
dentsu which grew out of japans wartime propaganda machine 
controls most government public relations and the largest chunk of 
all domestic advertising 
but critics charge dentsu also controls peoples minds an 
accusation that isnt exactly refuted by the companys own 
corporate credo manipulate those around you in the end the 
manipulative rise way above the manipulated 
i cant think of any other institution in the world that has 
the kind of molding power in society that dentsu does said karel 
van wolferen author of the enigma of japanese power 
the way in which the firm uses its power underscores the role of 
big coporations in general in postwar japan 
large japanese corporations have a certain interest in 
social control theres a strong sense of responsibility to 
maintain the social order said wolferen a dutch journalist who 
has lived in japan for 25 years 
one recent example of dentsus powers came last year when the 
nation was preparing for its first sales tax although the loudest 
protests against the levy came from housewives dentsu eye a 
dentsu subsidiary that focuses on the womans point of view 
promoted the tax 
this was because a group of dentsu eye executives came to a 
personal decision that the consumption tax was necessary said 
naoe wakita dentsu eye president 
her company designed a newspaper campaign that featured finance 
minister ryutaro hashimoto because he is considered handsome 
soliciting womens opinions on the tax 
the once vigorous movement to revise the tax has all but died 
dentsu with an army of 6000 employees and earnings last year 
of 131 billion bills itself as a total communications company 
involved in market research product testing sales promotion 
public relations megaevent planning and media brokering 
what the companys slick brochures dont say is that dentsu 
dominates the mass media in japan through its interlocking web of 
subsidiaries and contractors which among other things produce 
television programs and the ratings for those programs 
to an american that sounds like having your hand in the 
cookie jar but its common for large japanese companies to be 
affiliated with many other companies said caroline yamashita an 
american who worked at dentsus tokyo headquarters for two years 
dentsu spokesman ken kusuhara said dentsu grew up in the 
postwar period with todays large corporations so its natural that 
theres a close connection between us were like children who grew 
up together 
dentsus influence with the media is striking texas oilman t 
boone pickens recently tried to place ads in major japanese 
newspapers accusing toyota motor corp and other automakers of 
forcing high prices on consumers through collusive business 
practices 
pickens claimed that dentsu on client toyotas behalf used its 
clout with the media to block the ads his lawyer kanji ishizumi 
said dentsu told one of the newspapers that members of the japan 
automobile manufacturers association were very concerned about 
the ad appearing in newspapers 
the ads as originally submitted by pickens named toyota 
nissan motor co ltd and honda motor co ltd as the collusive 
culprits but when they were published a week after pickens went 
public with his charges the carmakers names were missing 
dentsu executive director teruyoshi kastsurada dismisses 
pickens charges dentsu does not have that kind of power and 
japanese newspapers are not so weak in their editorial positions 
that they would accept whatever dentsu tells them to do he said 
but japanese magazines have also accused dentsu of strictly 
controlling news reports of milk contaminated by a major client and 
reports of deaths linked to a cold medicine made by a client 
a dentsu executive boasted in a 1971 speech that japans largest 
newspaper the yomiuri shimbun after having invited consumer 
advocate ralph nader to japan heeded a warning from dentsu by 
toning down coverage of the visit that executive shohei kogure 
is now dentsus president 
dentsu handles close to 25 percent of all advertising budgets in 
japan placing more than 20 percent of ads in major newspapers and 
major chunks of advertising in magazines and on prime time 
television 
dentsus influence also extends to tv and the big screen the 
company and its affiliates produce a number of highprofile tv 
programs and movies it often uses the stars to offer clients 
advertising tieins merchandise sales and other promotional 
opportunities 
then theres dentsus role as a media broker it buys blocks of 
media time and sells it to advertisers thereby deciding who can 
sponsor a tv program and when 
for public relations work dentsu has been the top choice of the 
longruling liberal democratic party since japans first general 
election after the us occupation 
part of the companys power stems from its onetime merger with 
the monopolistic domei news service which churned out government 
propaganda between 1936 and 1945 of japans two major news 
agencies today kyodo news service owns 283 percent of dentsu 
stock and jiji press owns 201 percent 
with 90 percent of its business in japan dentsus one weakness 
is a lack of international experience observers say 
but the company has expansion plans since 1987 it has operated 
in 19 countries as hdm in partnership with us advertising giant 
young amp rubicam inc and frances eurocom it also formed a joint 
venture in 1988 with the american public relations firm 
bursonmarsteller 
dentsu executives say they want to expand into countries where 
their clients mostly japanese companies that have gone 
multinational are doing business 
</TEXT>
