<TEXT>
robert stempel took the wheel of general motors 
corp and steered the company more toward its factories than to 
wall street 
stempel who wednesday officially became the huge corporations 
chairman and chief executive officer is the first engineer to sit 
in gms corner office in the companys 82year history 
he succeeds roger smith who retired after 9 years as chairman 
a tenure marked by criticism that the accountant concentrated too 
much on earnings and not enough on engineering 
stempel and the six men he tapped to lead gm into the 1990s met 
with reporters wednesday morning and outlined changes in the 
corporations top management in essence stempel said 
responsibility lines were straightened between the companys eight 
car and truckmaking operations and gms top brass 
these are not major changes but theyre indicative of where 
were going he said were not taking general motors apart and 
putting it back together again 
stempels ascension to the chairmanship was widely hailed by 
industry observers who said the no 1 automakers product 
development programs had been unnecessarily put on a back burner as 
the company concentrated on boosting profits 
while smith was chairman gms balance sheet moved from a 3334 
million profit in 1981 to a 42 billion profit last year but the 
companys share of the us car and truck market dropped from 46 
percent to 35 percent during that same time 
stempel said the company planned to boost its market share but 
only if it can do it profitably 
the 90s will be a time of adapting and building what we have 
in place stempel said gm shuts down its lakewood assembly plant 
in atlanta on monday putting about 2000 employees out of work 
the company says no further plant closings are in the works other 
than those already announced 
lloyd reuss who became the companys new president wednesday 
said he expects 100 percent of gms assembly plants to be operating 
by 1992 he declined to say what percentage of gms plant capacity 
is being used now 
since 1987 when the company signed its last contract with the 
united auto workers union gm has shut down four assembly plants 
including the lakewood factory and plans to close part of its huge 
lordstown ohio complex when it consolidates fullsize van 
production in flint by 1992 
