<TEXT>
americans have had their fill of crises real or 
imagined and can hardly tolerate another it probably explains why 
the energy problem has fallen into the background 
but there is uncomfortable news in the background and it might 
be summarized in three sentences american production of crude oil 
is falling consumption is rising imports account for half of us 
supplies 
these ingredients mean an inevitable crisis the only unknown 
being its timing and extent the timing could be sometime in the 
next century it also could be as imminent as the next time warfare 
threatens in the middle east 
the us economy runs on energy that is the nations 
factories homes and means of transportation depend on it as 
history has demonstrated a shortage can stall an automobile or an 
economy with equal effectiveness 
recognizing this america went on an energysaving crusade 
beginning in the 1970s old homes and factories were insulated and 
standards for new ones were raised alternative energy supplies 
were encouraged and businesses for that purpose were founded 
much of that seems like a memory now akin to the lingering 
thoughts some people have of blackouts and ration cards during 
world war ii that deprivation ended suddenly people resumed their 
lives and said never again 
but the energy war never was won its ingredients remain and 
theyre just as explosive as ever a country totally dependent on a 
stable supply but with no assurance of it a country increasing 
energy usage but not its production 
domestic crude oil production in june fell to 71 million 
barrels a day the lowest on record that months output was 77 
percent below a year earlier and no less than 2 million barrels a 
day below the rate in february 1986 
drilling crews have disbanded and while exploration continues 
it is at a reduced rate increasingly the demand for oil runs 
headlong into the demands of environmentalists to protect the 
planets water wildlife and beauty 
the alternative is to import oil imports now are at a record 
high slightly exceeding the record of december 1977 when 479 
percent of the nations supply came from abroad while domestic 
output runs into environmental restrictions imported oil runs in 
opposition to balance of payment efforts 
no matter how it is viewed therefore energy in the form of 
crude and refined oil is a problem of deadly proportions potential 
or actual and it can erupt as easily as for example hostilities 
in the mideast 
in spite of this vulnerability of just about every individual 
business and governmental unit you dont hear much talk these 
days about energy supplies except perhaps to hear about another 
nuclear power facility unbuilt 
all the creative ideas of a decade ago are warehoused like old 
inventory many of the briefly successful alternative energy 
companies have collapsed the old conservation methods seem like 
holdovers from another time 
except for another oil spill energy doesnt make big news these 
days it has receded into the background overwhelmed by what are 
considered to be more urgent problems 
but the ingredients of crisis still are there everyone knows 
it and they know too that experience teaches that knowing is not 
enough 
</TEXT>
