<TEXT>
karsten mahlmanns resignation as chairman of the 
chicago board of trade is only the latest woe to befall the 
commodities industry in recent years 
since the 1987 stock market crash questions have been raised on 
whether the commodities futures trading commission is adequately 
regulating the industry and on the honesty of traders on the board 
of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange also given a serious 
look was the way the board of trade handled an alleged attempt to 
corner the soybean market by ferruzi trading international spa 
mahlmann resigned wednesday as chairman of the cbot the worlds 
largest commodity futures exchange amid allegations of wrongdoing 
at a trading company he headed he was midway through an 
unprecedented fourth term as the cbots chief 
mahlmanns resignation came hours after he announced his 
resignation as head of stotler group inc a beleaguered 
commodities company that operates a subsidiary accused of violating 
the commodity exchange act 
on tuesday the commodity futures trading commission filed a 
federal complaint accusing a stotler subsidiary of violating the 
commodity exchange act the complaint names stotler funds inc a 
commodity pool operator owned by stotler group 
the cftc contends stotler funds improperly used pools of 
clients money which had been set up for investing in commodity 
futures contracts to invest in stotler group stotler funds also 
lent 1 million from another pool to its parent company 
much more publicized problems in the futures industry culminated 
last month with the trial of three swiss franc futures traders but 
a federal jury ended up convicting two of the traders of only 
relatively minor trading violations and acquitting the third 
defendant of some offenses 
the jury couldnt reach verdicts on scores of other charges 
including a racketeering count against one defendant and mail and 
wirefraud charges against all three 
officials of the chicago mercantile exchange where the traders 
worked said the jurys action somewhat redeemed the markets 
reputation 
the twomonth trial was the first to result from an undercover 
fbi investigation of corruption at the merc and the board of trade 
in all 48 people have been indicted since august sixteen have 
pleaded guilty to reduced charges 
two other groups 13 soybean traders from the board of trade 
and 15 yen traders from the merc face trials in september 
the heavy scrutiny of commodities industry followed the oneday 
drop of more than 500 points in the dow jones industrial average 
a key market indicator in october 1987 and a 190point singleday 
drop last year 
a cftc study after the second drop indicated index arbitrage was 
not a major factor in the stock slide index arbitrage is a 
computerized program trading strategy that seeks to profit from 
differences between the stock and futures markets the study found 
no evidence of stock index futures market manipulation 
the security and exchange commission and other critics of index 
arbitrage contend it causes wild price swings index arbitragers 
try to take advantage of small price differences between the stock 
and futures markets by simultaneously buying large orders in one 
market while selling in another 
most stock index futures are traded on the chicago mercantile 
exchange 
to curb volatility the bush administration wants to move 
authority for stockindex futures from the cftc to the sec 
the cftc and the futures industry oppose any shift saying it 
will cripple the agencys ability to regulate other futures 
porducts and overregualate a segment of an industry that is trying 
to stave off foreign competition 
the board of trade came under heavy criticism from farmers and 
others last year after it moved to break up an attempt to corner 
the soybean market the cbot issued an emergency order requiring 
the liquidation of large positions in the july soybean futures 
contract 
the order targeted ferruzzi an italian agricultural and 
financial firm and one of the worlds largest soybean processors 
the order prompted soybean prices to tumble sharply with 
agricultural groups saying the action led to lower prices paid to 
producers 
cbot board members also were accused of conflict of interest in 
ordering the liquidations 
the cftc said reasonable grounds existed for the liquidation 
order and said it found no evidence of selfdealing by cbot 
officials who might have sold off their holdings after voting to 
issue the order 
