<TEXT>
aerospace giant pratt amp whitney facing 
leaner us defense budgets will eliminate 4000 jobs by 1993 
mostly in connecticut and florida the company announced today 
the company plans to eliminate about 2000 jobs from its 
connecticut maine and georgia operations which have a combined 
staff of about 28300 said curtis linke pratt amp whitneys vice 
president of communications most of the jobs are in connecticut 
which has a total work force of about 25400 
the remaining 2000 jobs will cut from pratt amp whitneys florida 
work force which now stands at 8400 
the reductions will be accomplished primarily through attrition 
but the jetengine maker has not ruled out the possibility of some 
layoffs linke said pratt amp whitney has a worldwide work force of 
about 45000 
the cutbacks would be the second big work force reduction in two 
years the company eliminated 2650 salaried jobs in 1988 and 1989 
citing intense competition 
pratt amp whitney which depends on defense contracts for about 35 
percent of its business in recent times has been trying to shift 
its operation to a more commercially oriented one to offset losses 
due to defense cutbacks 
the company the largest division of hartfordbased united 
technologies corp has plants in east hartford middletown 
southington and north haven 
in addition to cutbacks here and pratts complex in palm beach 
fla the company may eliminate jobs at plants in maine and 
georgia linke said 
because of its huge business supplying engines for passenger 
jets pratt amp whitney had hoped to avoid the sweeping cuts under 
way at manufacturers more dependent on defense contracts 
in february the president of pratt amp whitneys commercial 
engine group selwyn d berson said the growing airliner market 
was expected to forestall layoffs in connecticut for the 
foreseeable future 
the company has a 20 billion backlog of civilian engine orders 
assembly work for those orders have been spread out over a 10 year 
period lessening the companys ability to cushion immediate 
defense cuts 
with easing world tensions the budget ax is expected to come 
down on prattpowered air force planes such as the f15 and f16 
jet fighters the advanced tactical fighter and the c17 transport 
utc has already been forced to layoff hundreds of workers at 
other divisions including sikorsky aircraft in stratford and 
norden systems in norwalk because of defense cuts 
