<TEXT>
iraq has nearly doubled its share of world oil 
supplies by taking control of kuwait raising new risks for the 
united states and other nations heavily dependent on imported oil 
private energy experts said today 
that assessment came as president bushs chief economic adviser 
said the us economy should be able to withstand an increase in 
oil prices without being pushed into a recession 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers said even if the turmoil in the mideast resulted in a 25 
percent rise in oil prices it would likely have only a modest 
adverse impact on us economic growth 
fully onehalf of us oil supplies are imported although the 
combined shares of the american market for iraq and kuwait are less 
than 10 percent according to industry figures 
in june the latest month for which figures are available 
persian gulf oil represented 247 percent of total us oil 
imports according to the american petroleum institute the trade 
group for major oil companies a year earlier the figure was 222 
percent 
the united states imported about 24 billion in oil and other 
goods last year from iraq while us exports to iraq led by 
agricultural commodities totaled 117 billion in 1989 
iraq is one of the united states biggest trading partners in 
the arab world surpassed only by saudi arabia iraqs leading 
exports to the united states are crude oil and dates 
kuwaits exports to the united states also mainly oil totaled 
973 million last year kuwait imported 855 million in us goods 
led by motor vehicles and parts 
christopher flavin a vice president of the worldwatch 
institute said iraqs invasion of tiny kuwait may have little 
immediate effect on world oil supplies if the conflict does not 
escalate and kuwaiti oil workers cooperate with iraq 
a more troubling question flavin said is what step iraqi 
president saddam hussein might take toward seeking control of oil 
fields elsewhere on the arabian peninsula 
by grabbing kuwait saddam has boosted his share of world oil 
reserves to 20 percent iraq has about 100 billion barrels of 
reserves while kuwait has about 94 billion according to figures 
published this summer by british petroleum 
if iraq gained control of saudi arabia which ranks as the 
worlds largest oil exporter and the no 1 supplier to the united 
states it could garner enough economic clout to hold the world 
economy at risk flavin said 
saudi arabia with reported oil reserves of 255 billion barrels 
is the most oilrich nation in the world 
flavin estimated that an iraqi military move against saudi 
arabia and the smaller united arab emirates could give saddam 
control of 60 percent of total world oil reserves 
boskin told the congressional joint economic committee that the 
gross national product would be trimmed by a few tenths of a 
percentage point by a 25 percent rise in oil prices 
even if the higher price is enforced our economy today is 
much better able to absorb modest price increases boskin said 
but he conceded that a rise in world oil prices would have 
some deleterious impact on our economy the impact he said 
would be more harmful on the japanese economy because of its 
greater dependence on imports from opec 
boskins scheduled appearance before congress was to explain the 
administrations downward economic forecasts for 1990 and 1991 and 
the impact those revisions have had on the budget deficit 
</TEXT>
