<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of fellow opec member 
kuwait may have dealt a sharp blow to the cartels attempts at 
solidarity in restraining oil output and gradually raising world 
crude prices analysts said thursday 
although oil prices shot higher thursday following news of the 
invasion thursday analysts said the longterm impact of the 
assault possibly could be to weaken opecs attempts at controlling 
production 
iraq assaulted its muchsmaller neighbor less than a week after 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries signed an accord 
designed to restore production discipline to the sometimes unruly 
organization 
it takes that piece of paper puts a light to it and sends it 
up the chimney said peter gignoux director of the international 
energy department at shearson lehman hutton in london 
the invasion also reinforced suspicions that the cartel might be 
increasingly controlled by the whims of iraqi president saddam 
hussein 
saddams military threats against kuwait and the united arab 
emirates were seen as a motivating factor in last weeks agreement 
he had complained that his country lost 14 billion in oil revenue 
in the past year because kuwait and the uae cheated on their opec 
supply quotas and forced down crude prices 
it weakens the organization because one country now dominates 
completely and imposes its will on the others said peter 
bogin associate director for oil markets at cambridge energy 
research associates in paris 
but others said the invasion reflected changes that might signal 
greater discipline 
up until now the cartel lacked an enforcement mechanism 
said nauman barakat in shearsons energy department in new york 
we do now have that mechanism saddam hussein to make sure 
policies are enforced very vigorously 
there was no comment from opec this is a political thing 
said one cartel official demanding anonymity it has nothing to 
do with us 
the agreement signed last friday by all 13 nations boosted 
opecs target price to 21 a barrel from the 18 mark in effect 
since december 1986 iraq had argued for a 25 price 
analysts said the target was likely hit or even surpassed 
when crude prices surged thursday on worries that the iraqi 
