<TEXT>
union pilots who joined a strike against eastern 
airlines have the right to replace trainees hired during the 
carriers rebuilding a federal judge ruled thursday 
its clearly a major victory said ej breen spokesman for 
the air line pilots association which challenged an eastern claim 
that returning pilots were not needed 
but eastern planned to appeal the decision and officials said 
there will be no immediate effect on current employees or 
operations 
a statement by eastern indicated its appeal is likely to take 
some time 
all but 200 of the 3600 alpa pilots walked off the job in 
sympathy with striking machinists in march 1989 pilots ended their 
strike last november but fewer than 50 have been recalled to the 
miamibased airline alpa officials said 
in a 12page ruling us district court judge edward davis 
agreed with alpas claims that the federal railway labor act 
guarantees returning strikers job rights ahead of the newly hired 
trainees 
the court must balance competing interests the right of 
striking pilots to return to jobs against managements efforts to 
maintain the status quo throughout the strike davis wrote 
this court concludes the balance weighs in favor of reinstating 
in place of trainees 
breen said the exact number of jobs affected by the ruling 
likely will be determined through further hearings but alpa 
contends that at least 404 pilots were in training when pilots 
ended their strike in november and are subject to replacement 
eastern spokewoman karen ceremsak said the airline estimates 180 
jobs are affected by the ruling 
about 1400 former eastern pilots may still be interested in 
returning said alpa spokesman lou baldwin in miami many of the 
pilots were hired by other airlines following the strike that began 
march 4 1989 
eastern filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection five days 
after the strike began and presently operates about 800 flights 
from its prestrike service of 1040 
ms ceremsak said she does not believe davis ruling must 
receive bankruptcy court approval 
davis concluded easterns hiring of pilot trainees violated the 
railway labor act because the company did not bring on workers 
already qualified to fly regular flights the purpose of the act it 
to provide uninterrupted transportation service davis ruled 
contracting with unqualified persons for future employment as 
pilots does not serve to fill the void left by the striking pilots 
as least not until some later date davis wrote 
the ruling stems from an august 1989 court filing by eastern 
seeking a judgment that it need not replace newly hired pilots with 
returning pilots 
baldwin said the eastern pilots trainees annual pay of about 
27000 is significantly higher than the industry average the 
average prestrike pay at eastern for fully accredited pilots was 
about 65000 he said 
if davis ruling is upheld on appeal all returning pilots would 
need to go through several weeks of recertification training under 
the federal aviation administration eastern officials said 
