<TEXT>
kuwaits invasion of iraq shook financial 
markets around the world thursday sending oil prices the dollar 
and interest rates soaring and stock prices reeling 
crude oil rose 157 a barrel in new york futures trading and 
nearly 2 in london unleashing fears of a resurgence of inflation 
and a possible recession in the united states that affected other 
markets 
oil prices were boosted by the possibility the invasion 
eventually could affect output from the two nations or other 
members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
the september contract for west texas intermediate the 
benchmark grade of us crude rose 157 to 2311 a barrel on the 
new york mercantile exchange later months advanced 1 the limit 
for oneday advances in those contracts 
prices soared on the opening of trading with the september 
contract reaching 2380 but lost ground after reports circulated 
that iraq might withdraw its troops within 48 hours 
earlier in london the spot price of north sea brent blend the 
most widely traded international crude oil finished at 2239 a 
barrel up nearly 2 from wednesday but down from its highs of the 
day 
its been a rumordriven market said greg dreis a trader 
with merrill lynch energy futures 
traders said they had not seen oil prices shoot up as fast since 
1979 when the iranian revolution also raised concerns about the 
flow of oil from the middle east 
but trading was checked somewhat by the knowledge that other oil 
producers including opecs biggest member saudi arabia could 
increase their output and provide a safety valve against a severe 
drop in oil shipments 
they have the potential to make up for a substantial portion 
if not all of any deficit said william byers an analyst with 
bear stearns amp co 
trading was similar for the dollar which rose in early trading 
before falling back somewhat 
the us currency got a twofold boost the dollar is considered 
a safe haven for investors during world strife and it is the 
medium of exchange for crude oil analysts said traders who have 
shied away from it recently were buying heavily in early trading to 
adjust their holdings 
but the dollar which has been depressed in recent weeks because 
of the weakening us economy gave up some of its gains as foreign 
exchange traders later grew pessimistic about the economic 
ramifications of surging oil prices 
with oil and other energy sources crucial for every segment of 
the economy rising crude prices can reinvigorate inflation that 
would make the federal reserve which considers fighting inflation 
one of its top priorities less likely to move interest rates 
lower 
even if the fed eased credit it would be more tentative 
said raymond stone a managing director of stone amp mccarthy 
research associates inc 
if these oil prices stick it means the country will be that 
much closer to recession stone said 
the dollar closed at 15910 west german marks up from 158885 
late wednesday in new york trading the british pound which has 
stormed higher against the dollar recently slipped to 18545 from 
18552 
the japanese yen fell sharply as japan imports 99 percent of 
its oil and would be hurt by a surge in oil prices the dollar rose 
to 14930 yen from late thursdays 14730 
stock and bond prices also were depressed by fears about the 
economy 
on wall street traders were concerned about the effect oil 
prices would have on corporate profits heavy selling sent stock 
prices broadly lower 
the dow jones industrial average of 30 blue chip stocks dropped 
3466 points to 286460 on the broader market declining issues 
outpaced advancers by a margin of more than 5 to 2 on the new york 
stock exchange 
