<TEXT>
kansas gas and electric co urged 
stockholders thursday to reject a 27pershare 875 million 
takeover offer from kansas city power and light co 
kgampe said the offer made last month of 857 million in cash 
for its common stock and 18 million cash for three series of 
preferred stock was inadequate 
kcpl spokesman turner white said the utility still was willing 
to negotiate with kgampe but he said kcpl officials needed to study 
kgampes full response before deciding on their next move 
federal lawsuits have been filed by both utilities and two 
groups of kgampe stockholders in connection with the takeover attempt 
in documents filed with the securities and exchange commission 
in washington kgampe said its board decided last friday that the 
offer was inadequate and not in the best interests of the company 
and its shareholders 
kgampe did not indicate how much the offer fell short of its 
perceived value of the company 
kgampe said it was not involved in merger sale or reorganization 
talks with anyone the company said it does not believe kcpl has 
met conditions needed to require kgampe to provide a list of 
stockholders and call a special shareholders meeting 
the utility said it believes the offer could have adverse tax 
consequences for some shareholders and significant effects on 
employees customers and the communities kgampe serves 
white said kcpl does not plan to lay off any kgampe workers he 
said the utility would freeze customer rates until jan 1 1993 
and has a strong record of commitment to communities in its service 
area 
kgampe has excess generating capacity that kcpl would like to 
utilize to postpone building new generating plants 
kgampe said its strategies for the future include a carefully 
structured longterm plan for revenue enhancement from increased 
sales of power and energy in both wholesale and retail markets 
the filings also said kgampe was instituting further controls on 
capital and operating costs that would improve earnings without 
significantly increasing rates 
kgampe headquartered in wichita has 1330 employees and 254000 
customers in south central and southeast kansas its 1989 revenue 
was 5335 million and it reported net profits of 475 million 
kcpl headquartered in kansas city mo employs 2800 people 
and serves 409000 customers in western missouri and eastern 
kansas it made 1086 million on 730 million in revenue in 1989 
