<TEXT>
the scandalridden resignation of chicago board 
of trade chairman karsten mahlmann has helped revive a regulatory 
turf war that appeared to be winding down for lack of fuel 
within hours of mahlmanns announcement wednesday us reps 
john d dingell dmich and edward j markey dmass announced 
an investigation into the collapse of his brokerage firm with an 
emphasis on the adequacy of regulation and oversight in the 
futures industry 
on thursday one futures industry leader countered that the 
securities and exchange commission which regulates securities 
trading might be more to blame than the commodity futures trading 
commission which regulates futures trading for any failure to 
protect customers of mahlmanns trading company stotler group inc 
after all said david vogel chairman of the futures industry 
association as a futures brokerage trade group the sec had 
jurisdiction over stotlers offering of shares in two commodity 
investment funds that are at the center of federal allegations that 
stotler defrauded customers 
if anybody wants to start throwing stones its a little 
difficult to figure out who to throw stones at said vogel chief 
executive of the futures brokerage lit america inc 
i dont want to say the secs responsible but i dont think 
the cftcs responsible at all vogel said in a telephone 
interview 
the argument signals another round in the longrunning seccftc 
brawl for jurisdiction over stockindex futures 
the fall of cash mahlmann had nothing to do with stockindex 
futures which are contracts traded on futures exchanges that allow 
investors to speculate on stockmarket movements without ever 
owning stocks 
but mahlmanns problems have much to do with critics 
perceptions that the cftc is a lax regulator with a toocozy 
relationship with the industry it is supposed to be overseeing 
william hegen deputy regional administrator of the chicago sec 
office has said the sec tipped off the cftc to an allegedly 
improper transfer of 134 million in debt from a stotler unit to 
the parent company 
critics of the futures industry are likely to complain that the 
cftc should have been keeping a closer watch on stotler said james 
mcgurk a chicago commodities lawyer who has followed the seccftc 
turf battle 
the foes of the industry are going to use this he said 
the battle rages 
the fight had cooled recently amid waning congressional support 
for a bushadministration bill transferring jurisdiction over 
stockindex futures to the sec 
but stotlers collapse gives the sec and its supporters more 
ammunition mcgurk said 
now theyve got an answer were trying to do it better than 
these guys who couldnt do it thats the argument thats going to 
be advanced he said 
the fraud charges filed tuesday by the cftc were prompted by an 
alleged separate attempt to inject cash into the financially ailing 
stotler court documents allege that stotler funds inc an 
affiliate of stotler that operates commodity investment pools 
improperly transferred more than 5 million in customer funds to 
the parent company 
the funds were supposed to be used only for investment in 
commodity markets 
mahlmann has denied any involvement in stotlers recent 
financial decisions saying he was spending almost all his time 
running the board of trade 
