<TEXT>
major us oil companies said thursday they had 
small or no operations in kuwait and did not expect infrequent 
crude shipments from the country to be disrupted because of the 
invasion by neighboring iraq 
texaco inc operates the only refinery in either country a 
5050 joint venture with stateowned kuwait oil coin an area known 
as the neutral zone between kuwait and saudi arabia 
texaco spokeswoman anita larsen said about 80 percent of the 
refinerys 800 employees are saudi nationals and are 17 american 
she said operations were continuing despite the invasion 
gerald lastelic spokesman for the american petroleum institute 
in washington said the texacokuwait venture is the only 
usowned refinery operating in iraq or kuwait 
the texacokuwait refinery produces about 135000 barrels a day 
out of three fields larsen said 
eight american oil field workers were reported missing near the 
border of kuwait and company officials suspected they had been 
picked up by the invading iraqi army the state department said 
the whereabouts of the eight were unknown and state department 
officials would not identify the company for whom they work 
among other large american oil companies exxon corp mobil 
inc atlantic richfield co amoco corp and chevron corp all 
said they had no operations in kuwait and did not rely on oil from 
the middle east nation 
amoco spokesman michael thompson in chicago said that less than 
5 percent of the oil used in its us refineries was kuwaiti crude 
we have no reason to believe shipments from kuwait will be 
threatened he said and even if they were a shortterm loss 
of kuwait oil would not hinder our us refining operations 
chevron spokesman larry shushan said from his companys san 
francisco headquarters we do from time to time of course take 
oil from ports in that area it obviously is something we are quite 
concerned about because we are not going to be sending any ships 
into a war zone 
royal dutch shell group the european parent of shell oil co 
has one employee of a lubricants subsidiary in kuwait spokesman 
norman altstedter said but no other operations 
he said shell oil imports no oil from kuwait but 60000 to 
80000 barrels a day from iraq about 6 percent of its crude oil 
capacity shortterm needs would be covered by inventories but 
altstedter said some adjustments may be needed on the companys 
longer term purchasing requirements 
exxon issued a statement saying it has imported some oil from 
iraq to the united states in recent months we are currently 
evaluating our situation and taking steps to minimize any impact on 
our customers worldwide it said 
although none of the companies was directly affected us oil 
company stocks rose sharply on news of the invasion which boosted 
oil prices 
in new york stock exchange trading texaco gained 250 to 
6650 amoco rose 287 to 5825 chevron rose 162 to 
8037 mobil was up 187 to 6725 atlantic richfield was up 
487 to 13537 exxon rose 1 to 5312 and unocal was up 
212 to 3325 
