<TEXT>
delta air lines and the air line pilots 
association agreed thursday to a new contract that the union said 
included 125 percent pay raises that would make the carriers 
pilots the industrys bestpaid 
the tentative agreement follows 19 months of direct negotiations 
between the company and alpa which represents about 7600 pilots 
at delta 
we are pleased that weve been able to reach a tentative 
agreement without having to resort to mediation said capt gary 
holcombe chairman of the delta pilots master executive council 
this contract is industryleading in all aspects and one that 
will both compensate delta pilots fairly and give delta the 
resources it needs to continue to grow holcombe said 
delta spokesman neil monroe said the airline was pleased the 
agreement was made but said the company had no further comment 
alpa said the agreement calls for pay increases totaling 125 
percent until the contract can be amended in 1993 a statement by 
the union said it would make the delta pilots highest paid in the 
industry however the union was not able to provide figures on 
topscale salaries 
alpa spokesman rhea nicolls said under the terms of the 
agreement the starting salary for new hires including hourly pay 
during their training would rise from 1800 a month to 2500 
the agreement also calls for the elimination of deltas twotier 
wage system which pays newer employees at a lower rate than 
veterans in the fourth and fifth years of a pilots employment 
beginning sept 1 1992 nicolls said such pay scales have been 
common in the industry though disliked by pilots since airline 
deregulation 
this is a big breakthrough in the airline industry he said 
the contract will be formally written over the next four weeks 
and will be submitted to delta pilots for ratification 
